This paper deals with the topic of censorship circumvention, which falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). The use of video games as a covert channel involves network infrastructure and communication protocols, which also falls under the category of computer networks (cs.NI). The paper also discusses the diversity of video games and their server infrastructure, which could fall under the category of distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC). The implementation of the coding scheme over two real-time strategy games involves graphics and visualization, which could fall under the category of computer graphics (cs.GR). Finally, the paper discusses the potential use of the system for organizing political actions, which could fall under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI).
